					<h3><i class="icon-comment-alt"></i></i> Toi tu te kupu, toi tu te mana, toi tu te whenua</h3><p>
					This proverb was spoken by <a href="http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-TayTeik-t1-body-d1-d8.html"> Tinirau of Whanganui</a>. It is a plead to hold fast to our culture, for without language, without mana (spirit), and without land, the essence of being who we are would no longer exist, but be a skeleton which would not give justice to the full body of Maoritanga (maoridom). </p>
					
					<p>I have no Maori blood but I've spent more time in the hills and forests than most Maori ever have and I strongly identify with what Tinirau is saying. I also come from Whanganui and have always felt the pull of the wilderness.  </p>

					<p>When I was a teenager I was blessed by an old Maori Queen at Putiki Marae. I was walking past and she called me over and told me she could see the spirit of Tane of the forest watching over me and no harm would ever befall me in the bush. This has indeed proved true my entire life despite falling over cliffs and getting hopelessly lost countless times (always found my own way out though... eventually... took me three days once).					

				</div>
